Insulin helps move sugar into your cells to give them energy. With diabetes, the amount of sugar in your blood increases, causing various health issues. There are two main types: Type 1 and Type 2.

Type 1 Diabetes:
In this type, your pancreas stops producing enough insulin. As a result, you need regular insulin injections or an insulin pump to survive. It usually develops during childhood or adolescence but can occur at any age.

Type 2 Diabetes:
With this type, the body doesn't use insulin properly (a condition called insulin resistance). Over time, your pancreas has trouble making enough insulin for the glucose in your blood. You may need oral medications or injections to manage it. Type 2 is more common and often associated with lifestyle factors, such as obesity and physical inactivity.

Both types can lead to serious complications if not managed properly, like heart disease, nerve damage, kidney damage, vision problems, and even amputations. Regular monitoring of blood sugar levels, medication adherence, healthy eating habits, and exercise can help manage diabetes effectively.
